docs.snippet: PINCUS--Dr. Murray Benjamin, 92, a renowned surgeon of urology and a professor of medicine at Mt. Sinai Hospital for over 45 years, died peacefully at his home in Manhattan on Wednesday, October 7. He is survived by his devoted wife of 50 years An...
docs.lead_paragraph:
PINCUS--Dr. Murray

Benjamin, 92, a renowned surgeon of urology and a professor of medicine at Mt. Sinai Hospital for over 45 years, died peacefully at his home in Manhattan on Wednesday, October 7. He is survived by his devoted wife of 50 years Ann, his beloved daughters Beth (Andrew) and Lynn, and his adoring grandchildren Jake and Rachel. Dr. Pincus received both his BA and his MD from the University of Virginia, earning the highest honors of Phi Beta Kappa and Alpha Omega Alpha. Dr. Pincus was also affiliated with the Peter Bent Brigham Hospital in Boston and served as Chief of Urology at Elmhurst Hospital in New York. Dr. Pincus was published in numerous medical journals and served with distinction as a Captain in the US Air Force during the Korean War. Funeral services will be held in private.

docs.lead_paragraph:
STUBING--William Charles,

76, died October 4, receiving home hospice care after struggling with a brain prion disease. He was unafraid to face death, although he loved life and the people around him. He was a loving and devoted partner for 37 years and husband for two of those years. His friendship, counsel, and dinner invitations were eagerly sought by friends, family, and colleagues. His guidance shaped the current form of the New York Academy of Medicine and The Greenwall Foundation. The latter's work in bioethics supported many leaders in the area. He wanted to make end-of-life decisions easier for those in need of such decisions. He was pastoral and loved the good things in life: good food, glorious music, and particularly old friends. A private service will be held at St. Thomas Episcopal Church. In lieu of flowers, donations may be made to the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
